>anthros being unable to bear human children
I know you're just a misanthropic furry trying to bait, but may as well use this as an opportunity.
Really though I think in a world where humans and anthros existed a world war would likely end up being fought between humans and their allies and a large coalition of anti-human anthro states. As weird as it might seem at first glance I think humans would likely ally with many of the prey animals in a strange sort of horseshoe theory but for the food chain. Now this very well might come just as a result of many predator species going against humans due to believing that without humans they could become the apex predator, or simply from not liking having such a sword of Damocles ever present on the global political landscape. Rodents and lagomorphs (not biased though) would almost certainly side with humans at least in part due to being so closely related, though I could see an argument being made for rats going against humans, or even potentially heading the anti-human coalition, due to them being just about the only others anywhere near dexterous enough to create technology requiring fine craftsmanship on their own. Depending on who most rodents side with would play a large role in determining if the humans would be mostly on the defensive or a much more offensive war. Without rodents the humans end up at a serious numbers disadvantage, thus forcing them to be significantly more careful about ensuring they don't make many risky moves and not needlessly lose manpower. It would end up being far more of a war of attrition with humans using their defensive and technological capabilities to drag the war out long enough to give them some notable trump card. (cont.)

>>34506773
Sort of like the atom bomb in WWII, except if it was actually a necessity to win. However, if the rodents do side with the humans then there's honestly not much that could be done against them. In this scenario the humans would have an enormous manpower, industrial, and technological advantage, and this would only become vastly more exacerbated as the war went on. Not only would they be able to play far more varied and risky with their equipment but they would also be able to with their armies as well. They could launch incredibly aggressive attacks and even if they could very high casualties it would be an inconvenience to them but a massive blow to the enemy (though they almost certainly wouldn't do this anyways simply due to the lack of necessity to). Ultimately, the capabilities that humans could bring to the table would be far too much unless it was literally humans versus the entire world, and even then the outcome is still up for debate depending on the terrain the humans would be defending in. In the event of a human victory what would happen after the fact is perhaps even more debatable than during, but one fairly likely thing is apartheid states being established with humans as their rulers. Technological dependence on humans would likely only grow as technology requiring finer and finer engineering came into existence.

That might work against some species but
A) Humans are and still would be by far the best with ranged weaponry (really not too much to say here, a range advantage is enormous, especially when your enemy is basically only melee).
B) Humans would still outnumber any attackers by and large (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mammal look at the pie chart for a very general overview of the most basic breakdown of how different populations would roughly relate to one another, would almost certainly change drastically as the world advanced and got safer though).
C) Humans are at the top of the pyramid, other species have an instinctual aversion to attacking humans (yes, yes, I know they'd be thinking with logic due to being sapient and not behaving the same way their wild animal counterparts do but instincts still have great effects even on us that are simply difficult to see).
D) Technological advancement is effectively inevitable and simple international conflicts aren't going to do much to hinder it on the larger scale (unless humans are basically the sole keepers of most knowledge for a while and their Library of Alexandria gets totally toasted).
E) Tool precision doesn't become the main factor until a very long time has passed of simple dexterity being king (even then, you still need a certain base level of dexterity to be able to properly maintain the tools that maintain the machines that give you your advantage over the naturally dexterous or else your stuff starts falling into disrepair and eventually becomes unusable).
F) Predators that get much of their capabilities from their size wouldn't be nearly as extreme as they are in our world due to the size normalization that people here typically apply (and going with Zootopia size bs isn't a real option without the Disney magic to prop it up, it would also make plenty of things in this conversation effectively null and void, not to say it can't make for an interesting story, just very different from this).
